1258** ‚Äî status: running, started: ~03:03 UTC (startedAt: 1776162044660), last update: 1776210112732 (~22:21 UTC). Running ~19h 48m.\\n4. **agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:direct:6053576134** ‚Äî status: done. The last message was the status report at 23:41 UTC.\\n5. **agent:master-orchestrator:main** ‚Äî status: done.\\n6. **agent:master-orchestrator:cron:53c5832a** ‚Äî status: done (no status field, but no status:\\\"running\\\" either).\\n\\nNow I'm recalculating the durations more carefully by working backwards from the current timestamp of 1776210694251 to figure out exactly when each session started.\\n\\nThe cron:e7885813 session just started itself at 23:51 UTC, so it's running but I should exclude it. That leaves three active sessions: the QLHV progress report cron that's been running for about 49 minutes, the DTLX progress report cron that's been active for roughly 3 hours, and the Telegram group channel that's been going for around 2 hours.\\n\\nLooking at the timing more carefully, I'm realizing the cron job sends updates every 5 minutes, but the last actual status report to Telegram was at 23:41 UTC‚Äîwhich means the 5-minute cycle should have triggered another update around 23:46, though I'm not seeing that in the logs.\\n\\nSince the cron:e7885813 session just started at 23:51 UTC, it's about 10 minutes old and appears to be one of the monitoring cron jobs. I'm checking the timestamps on the other cron sessions to understand the pattern‚Äîthe older ones ran at 23:49 and 23:49 UTC, but this one is fresh, so it seems like the system is cycling through multiple cron jobs throughout the hour.\\n\\nLooking at the running sessions now: the QLHV Progress Report cron started around 22:02 UTC and has been active for about 1 hour 49 minutes, the DTLX Progress Report cron has been running for roughly 3 hours 5 minutes, and the Telegram group session started much earlier at around 16:03 UTC and is still going.\\n\\nSince the pipeline is healthy with no block